    <p>In 2026, there are 261 weekdays and 104 weekend days. After subtracting federal holidays that fall on weekdays, the number of business days is approximately 250. Use our <a href="/date-calculators/business-days-calculator/">business days calculator</a> to find the exact number of business days between any two dates.</p>

    <h2>Work Weeks and Working Days in 2026</h2>
    <p>While a year has 52 calendar weeks, the number of actual work weeks is considerably lower once you account for holidays, vacation, and sick time. Here is a breakdown of how 365 days translate into actual working time for a typical full-time employee in the United States.</p>
    <div class="table-responsive">
      <table>
        <thead>
          <tr><th>Category</th><th>Days</th><th>Weeks Equivalent</th></tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td>Total days in 2026</td><td>365</td><td>52.14</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Weekend days (Sat + Sun)</td><td>104</td><td>14.86</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Total weekdays</td><td>261</td><td>52.20</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Federal holidays on weekdays</td><td>11</td><td>2.20</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Business days (excl. holidays)</td><td>250</td><td>50.00</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Average PTO (vacation + sick)</td><td>15</td><td>3.00</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Actual working days</td><td>235</td><td>47.00</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>
    <p>The average American worker with 10 vacation days and 5 sick days actually works about 235 days, or approximately 47 five-day work weeks. Workers with more generous PTO packages (20+ vacation days is common at senior levels) may work even fewer — around 230 days or 46 work weeks. Understanding this number is important for freelancers setting rates, businesses planning capacity, and anyone calculating their true hourly wage from an annual salary.</p>

    <h2>Pay Periods in 2026: Weekly, Biweekly, Semi-Monthly, and Monthly</h2>
    <p>Employers pay workers on different schedules, and the number of pay periods per year varies by type. This affects how much you receive per paycheck if you are salaried, and it can impact budgeting, tax withholding, and automatic transfers. The table below shows the four common pay frequencies.</p>
    <div class="table-responsive">
      <table>
        <thead>
          <tr><th>Pay Frequency</th><th>Pay Periods per Year</th><th>Paycheck Amount ($60,000 salary)</th><th>Notes</th></tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td>Weekly</td><td>52</td><td>$1,153.85</td><td>Paid every week (e.g., every Friday)</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Biweekly</td><td>26</td><td>$2,307.69</td><td>Paid every 2 weeks; some years have 27</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Semi-monthly</td><td>24</td><td>$2,500.00</td><td>Paid twice per month (1st and 15th)</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Monthly</td><td>12</td><td>$5,000.00</td><td>Paid once per month</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>
    <p>The biweekly vs. semi-monthly distinction confuses many workers. Biweekly means every 14 days (typically every other Friday), resulting in 26 paychecks. Semi-monthly means twice per month on fixed dates (like the 1st and 15th), resulting in exactly 24 paychecks. Biweekly paychecks are smaller ($2,307.69 vs. $2,500 on a $60,000 salary) but you receive two extra per year. Over the full year, the total is the same — $60,000 either way.</p>

    <h3>The 27th Paycheck Problem</h3>
    <p>Because a year is not exactly 52 weeks, biweekly pay schedules occasionally produce 27 pay periods in a calendar year instead of 26. This happens approximately once every 11 years. When it occurs, salaried employees either receive a slightly smaller per-check amount (annual salary divided by 27 instead of 26) or receive the same per-check amount and effectively earn a small "bonus" — depending on how the employer handles the anomaly. For 2026, most biweekly pay schedules will have the standard 26 pay periods, but it depends on the specific start date of the pay cycle.</p>
    <p>Hourly workers on biweekly pay are not affected by this issue since they are paid for actual hours worked. The 27th paycheck only impacts the per-check math for salaried workers whose annual salary is divided across the pay periods.</p>

    <h2>Leap Years: When and Why</h2>
    <p>A leap year adds one day (February 29) to the calendar, making the year 366 days instead of 365. The purpose is to keep the calendar aligned with the Earth's orbit around the Sun, which takes approximately 365.2422 days. Without leap years, the calendar would drift about 24 days every century, eventually causing summer months to fall in winter.</p>
    <p>The rules for determining leap years are more complex than most people realize. A year is a leap year if it is divisible by 4 — except years divisible by 100 are not leap years, unless they are also divisible by 400. This means 2024 was a leap year (divisible by 4), 1900 was not (divisible by 100 but not 400), and 2000 was (divisible by 400). The year 2026 is not a leap year. The next leap year is 2028.</p>
